# Coding Standards

## TypeScript

- `strict: true` is assumed. No `any` without an explicit reason commented above it.
- Use `import type { Foo }` for type-only imports.
- Prefer `const` objects with `as const` over enums.

## React

- Functional components, named exports.
- One component per file (except tiny colocated helpers).
- Hooks live next to the component that owns them, unless reused by ≥2 components → move to `src/funnel/hooks/`.

## Files & folders

- `kebab-case` for directories, `PascalCase.tsx` for component files, `camelCase.ts` for utilities and hooks.
- No `index.ts` barrel files inside `src/funnel/**` — they hurt tree-shaking and jump-to-definition.

## Imports

- Remove unused imports before finishing. Treat "unused import" as a lint error.
- Group order: Node/react → third-party → `@/` aliases → relative. A blank line between groups.

## Comments

- Do NOT narrate what the code does (no `// increment counter`).
- Only comment non-obvious intent, constraints, or trade-offs.
- Prefer better names over explanatory comments.

## Formatting

- Prettier handles formatting. After any change, run:

```sh
{ git diff --name-only HEAD; git ls-files --others --exclude-standard; } | xargs npx prettier --write --ignore-unknown
```

## Don'ts

- No `console.log` in committed code. Use the analytics `track()` wrapper for telemetry or a real logger.
- No dead code "for later". Delete it; git remembers.
- No inline styles when a Chakra prop or Tailwind class exists.
